column1: just wanted to let you guys know that we have added a new section to our blog where you can share your story.

part of our healing process has been to share our story and stand up for the injustices that have been allowed to happen. so many of you have reached out to us with your own personal story of abuse and corruption
column2: so we wanted to open the invitation up to everyone who has something to say
column3: who have had similar experiences. there is healing when you speak your truth. i know it's terrifying at first but it will give you freedom. and you may remain anonymous if you would like. .

column1: i'm still trying to come up with the words to describe my experience and feelings...sometimes i have none and just cry.
i cry out of frustration that the leaders at christian faith center want to minimize the abuse and crimes by saying
column2: ""it happened a long time ago."" as if saying that makes it less real or valid. the pain that these women
column4: and their families have experienced is very real no matter when it happened.

column2: for others it wasn't years ago
column3: the abuse is much more recent
column4: which saddens me that the toxic culture is a breeding ground for abuse by leadership to continue.

column1: one thing that i have learned is just because we pointed out a problem
column2: does not make us the problem.

column2: jesus has been my rock. as i learn to rest in the lord
column3: i know that he is in charge.

we win. maybe not now. but eventually.

column1: facing the abyss of the hero’s journey is a painful process that cannot be avoided if one is to rise in strength on the other side.  my own journey through an abyss filled with both childhood and spousal abuse left me near broken.  at a time when i contemplated suicide as a means of escape
column2: the hero with a thousand faces found its way to me.  campbell’s analysis of the monomyth led me along the arduous journey toward healing

column3: and the culmination of my healing came from finding the strength to self publish my work. one of my books
column5: is a poetry collection that explores the effects of and recovery from rape and sexual abuse. i felt compelled to publish as a means of reaching out to other survivors.  sadly
column7: my own work has been turned against me as i still face the accusatory words
column9: these two words most often preceded an attack
column10: usually coming as an effort to silence

column1: the #metoo movement has renewed my courage to hold my head high and refuse to cower under the shadow of someone else’s shame. i will not hide. i did not invite the attack on my eight year old self; i shall be the one to stand tall for that little girl when no one else would and face “i heard…” with dignity.  i will fight for her and for others who have also faced the rumor mill that spits out
column3: and you heard it from me.

column1: 192139;instagram;2019-01-26 05:47:19;FALSE;"chronique • 439 pages dévorées en moins de 24 heures. voilà
column2: ça vous donne une petite idée de ce qui vous attend en ouvrant anatomie d'un scandale
column3: le dernier page-turner haletant de sarah vaughan.

column1: le pitch 💙 une avocate qui vient de se voir confier l'affaire de sa vie
column2: face à un homme politique accusé du viol de sa secrétaire
column5: prête à tout pour préserver sa famille. l'une veut le détruire
column6: l'autre veut le sauver à tout prix.

column1: dans cette intrigue palpitante sur fond contemporain (mais ni putassier
column3: sarah vaughan ausculte chapitre après chapitre les états d'un scandale en train de se nouer. c'est riche
column5: adroit et terrible à la fois
column6: le genre que tu ouvres et que tu ne lâches plus.

column1: qui du député ou la secrétaire ment ? qui de l'avocate ou de l'épouse aura gain de cause ? le combat est intense
column5: le roman réserve sa petite surprise finale.

column2: c'est avant tout le choix judicieux de l'auteur de ne pas s'enfermer dans un point de vue unique : on passe de l'avocate à l'épouse et de l'épouse à l'avocate pour observer le récit se rapporter au travers de leur regard subjectif - un subterfuge malin pour préserver le dénouement et accrocher d'autant plus le lecteur curieux.

column1: #2 le rythme soutenu du roman qui s'affranchit de la lenteur des procédés judiciaires pour n'en garder que les passages les plus incroyables
column2: comme le contre-interrogatoire de la victime
column4: donne cette dynamique saccadée et vibrante
column5: ambiance feuilleton scandale à la dsk.

column1: #3 des personnages fouillés et complexes étoffent une intrigue déjà poignante
column2: avec des twists à la olivia pope et les piliers de tout bon scandale : sexe

column1: le genre de roman à lire d'urgence. et à retenir.

column1: no one is asking men to be anything other than men. we’re not telling them that they shouldn’t be masculine. we’re asking them to heal the toxic masculinity that has been oppressing women for thousands of years.
so thank you to the men who knew me in high school and college and treated me as a human

column3: we thank you. this isn’t an attack on men
column5: a reclamation. we can all be better

column1: 192176;instagram;2019-01-26 07:26:30;FALSE;"i had an interesting conversation tonight with my friend who is a relatively new quadriplegic. it was about the stereotypes of the severely disabled that he is now confronting six months into this journey. he says that sometimes people expect things from him that he can’t be
column2: and when he doesn’t perform “the happy cripple” or the “inspirational success story” he feels guilty and unseen. this is going off like fireworks for him and i’m like... yes! yes! me too! me. too. #metoo

column1: him and i have a unique bond. we met each other at our lowest. we both know each other to be deeply flawed
in that instant we met again as equals. yes
column3: too. i am only human. please don’t treat me as your hero
column6: or your whore. all i want to be is me. and all i want is for that to be okay

column1: « monsieur weinstein maintient qu’il est innocent et nous avons hâte de pouvoir l’assister dans sa défense »

column2: 남자를 뜻하는 픽토그램보다 다리가 얇다. 무대의상은 더 말할 것도 없이 심각하다. 겨울에도 짧은 의상은 기본에 조금만 살이 붙어도 여자아이돌에게 심각한 욕설을 퍼붓는다. 아직 페미니즘을 배우고 있어서 잘 모르지만 코피노 방임문제의 핵심인 일명 '한남'을 남자로 일방화시켜 모든 남자들은 '한남'이라 말하지 않듯 일부 과격한 페미니스트를 일반화시켜 페미니스트를 너무 나쁘게만 보지 않았으면 좋겠다( 레디컬 페미니스트의 주장에 의하면  과격하지 않고 사근사근하게 말하면 듣지도 않기 때문에 과격하게 운동하는 것이라고 한다. 어느정도 일리가 있다고 본다. ) * 페미니즘을 배우고 있는 사람이기에 잘못 알고 있는 부분이 있을 수 있습니다.  둥글둥글하게 지적/조언하시면 더 배우겠습니다. 비방이나 이유없는 악플시 각오 단단히 해두세요. *";;en;#마마무코르셋OUT

poisonous relationships can alter our perception. you can spend many years thinking you’re worthless… but you’re not worthless

column1: 192373;instagram;2019-01-26 14:53:26;FALSE;"a quick fun painting for one of my best bud’s birthday. i’ve struggled the last year or so with my mental state and painting. depression to me is always one of those nasty little voices that tell me i’m not good enough
column3: nobody cares about me or my work and unfortunately ive believed it....for a long time. luckily
column4: i have some really great friends and family that remind me and can help shut the negativity out. there’s no love like loving someone through their demons. i’m really excited for a commission that i’m finishing up...it’s taken a lot longer than it should have because i fought myself through the whole process but i’m incredibly proud of the finished product. stay tuned!....

column2: mary beard addresses in one brave book the misogynists and trolls who mercilessly attack and demean women the world over
column6: she traces the origins of this misogyny to its ancient roots
column7: examining the pitfalls of gender and the ways that history has mistreated strong women since time immemorial. as far back as homer’s odyssey
column9: women have been prohibited from leadership roles in civic life
column10: public speech being defined as inherently male. from medusa to philomela (whose tongue was cut out)
column11: from hillary clinton to elizabeth warren (who was told to sit down)
column12: beard draws illuminating parallels between our cultural assumptions about women’s relationship to power—and how powerful women provide a necessary example for all women who must resist being vacuumed into a male template. with personal reflections on her own online experiences with sexism
column13: beard asks: if women aren’t perceived to be within the structure of power
column14: isn’t it power itself we need to redefine? and how many more centuries should we be expected to wait?

column1: after reading marcus borg's intro to 1 thessalonians
column2: i am reading thessalonians! i'm at 1 thessalonians 3-4.

column1: it has been such a long time since i read through paul's letters. i am struck
column3: at how confusing it would be if this was the start of your #christian journey. imagine
column4: your first introduction to the church being based on this letter from a man who never met the earthly jesus. it's a lot.

column2: i am also struck by the call to purity. this is up and against dedicating your lives to god. there was a practice of sacred prostitution in the greek/roman way of religion. in the context of the word dedication
column3: i am imagining part of the command is to stop going to those temples. and part of it is to get control of yourself. and part of it is to not mistreat or take advantage of others sexually.

column1: i am also struck by the idea that getting control of themselves sexually is culturally contextual up against the gentile practice of sacred prostitution. when we consider sexual purity for today
column2: perhaps it is up and against practices of sexual mistreatment and/or taking advantage of others. #metoo

column3: what religious leaders are thinking when they endorse a certain politician that rhymes with rump when it is clear that he is in violation of this pauline exhortation. the text says
column4: ""whoever rejects these instructions … is rejecting god."" (v. 4:8). rump has rejected god. those religious leaders who endorse rump also reject god.

column1: the challenge for #leaders from paul is how to call people to better behavior without demoralizing them. gentle encouragement. he finishes with reminders of their loving deeds. how can we do that?

column1: 192452;instagram;2019-01-26 15:59:26;FALSE;"this past week has been laborious. and i hadn't even realized it until last night. i've had incredible urges to binge every single day this week. i've woken up in pain every day. i've not wanted to workout a single day this week. and i honestly blamed it on that wolf blood moon. (blood wolf moon?) but it wasn't that. it's because today makes 10.

column2: i was raped. by 2 men who i had never met and hope to never see again. that day
column3: was the worst day of my life.

column2: i found out i was pregnant.

column1: fast forward many years and lots of therapy later and my big take away is this:
what have you allowed to define you?

column2: it was fear. it ruled my life. it ruled when i went out. where i went. who i was with. then
column3: it was anger. why me? and why a baby from this horrifying thing? i have an answer for that one. there's no 👏🏻way 👏🏻 i would have made it out alive without jordan. no. way. .

column1: so what do i allow to define me now? my strength. in all the ways you can take that word
column2: that's what defines me now. strength of the mind. strength of the body. strength of the heart. that's not to say that i'm over it. i'll never get over it. that i don't have times where i'm not ok. because it's ok to not be ok. but if you want a chance a fulfilling life
column3: you have to put in work. try some therapy. that could look like going to a therapist. or going to the gym. or journaling. or hiking or screaming in the shower. just get👏🏻it👏🏻out👏🏻 being angry at someone for hurting you takes so much energy. energy that could be much better spent using on healing yourself. because you deserve the healing. the people who hurt you
column5: absolutely. but they don't get to take up space in your soul. that soul is yours. don't you let them have it.

column1: i don't have all the answers. no one does. but we each have experiences that shape us. that give us the ability to share and hopefully offer something of value to someone else through those experiences. be a decent human. help others by sharing what you can
column2: when you can. try not to let trauma define who you are. reach out. i'm here to listen if you choose to share with me.

column1: 192470;instagram;2019-01-26 16:25:39;FALSE;"she wants it by jill soloway is one of the most inspiring books i have ever read! 💘 thank you @crownpublishing for sending this review copy my way!
jill soloway is the creator of transparent
column3: that revolves around a los angeles family and their lives following the discovery that the person they knew as their father mort is a trans woman.

column1: this book is phenomenal on so many levels. 💗 it’s important to state that this isn’t a non-fiction book about being genderqueer or about feminism. this is soloway's memoir and
column3: it explores these ideas! this amazing book taught me about non-binary/transgender people and what they face on a daily basis! at a certain point
column4: soloway didn’t identify as male or female so the writer took on the personal pronoun 'they'.

column2: the author also explores matters of female sexuality and addresses  some feminist notions like the male gaze. soloway talks about being in a relationship with men and women and the ways it can be different and even discusses the porno industry.

column1: she wants it also depicts a controversial moment of the show. when the #metoo movement kicked off
column4: was accused of harassment by his female colleagues. hence
column5: soloway was suddenly put in a very sensitive situation. i liked how honest she was about this moment!

column2: the writer also shares feelings and fears when it comes to creation: the constant rejection
column5: soloway is definitely an artist! the writing was spectacular! heartfelt

column1: have you read this one? do you want to? can you think of similar books? i would love to read more like she wants it!!

column1: i hope y'all aren't tired of art news
column2: because i have more! a while back a dear friend of mine @allisonleighsmith started a collective of female artists in durango inspired by the #metoo movement
column3: but more broadly to create a space for female creative voices. she and @mariahkfa put together an incredible show called ""season of sanguinity"" that will open at animas chocolate company during snowdown.

column2: take a break from your snow-related superhero activities and stop by to enjoy the work of some seriously talented women (i might buy you a hot chocolate if you come in dressed as wonder woman 😊)! my drawing of ""cecilia payne"" will be featured along with a diverse collection of quality work. and of course... come by the durango arts center to see the painting of cecilia in my solo show at the barbara conrad gallery this month!

even when you're trying not to cry & the tears are blurring your vision.
even when people stare at you & tell you your voice is crappy.

even when your mind makes no sense of what you see.
even when you are made fun of.
even when you're afraid of what the dreams might bring.
even when it feels like you can't run any more.
even when the memories pinch your heart.

column1: because the pain of all your experiences are what make you the person you are now. and without your experiences
what makes you brave is your willingness to live life through the tough times & still hold your head high the next day.

column2: because you are stronger now after all the crap that has happened
column3: then you ever were back before it started.

column1: for me 2️⃣0️⃣0️⃣9️⃣ was a milestone year in my life as i relocated from rhodes
column2: greece to nyc to enter ☝️ of the most competitive specialty programs @columbia university.

column1: what are the most important things i learned through my journey ❓❓❓❓✍️ *
▪️ 1. leaving the comfort of my family& friends back 🏠 i had to learn to enjoy spending time with myself. i had to train myself to learn to have a nice dinner by myself
column3: enjoy a nice sunday morning by myself. for those you have have experienced this

column1: 2. work hard and at the end you will succeed.  i studied dental school in greece
column2: graduated 1️⃣st from my university. when i arrived at columbia there were so many skills that were missing. i was going to the lab early
column3: practicing over& over and working many times during lunch time… end result: i graduated with honors from my postgraduate program and was the most productive resident 😁👍just stay focused and work hard. opportunities are there.🙌🧠

column1: 3. find your tribe. as a female greek dentist
column2: there were instances that people will criticize me of my looks (``being pretty and smart may intimidate people``)
column3: my accent (``you speak too fast because you are a foreigner``)
column4: my gender (``you can’t have a family and a career). if i had given those people the power to affect me i would not be in this amazing situation that i live in the present. accept criticism
column5: people will always want to share their opinion
column6: but please select the right vibe in your reality. 👫👭👯‍♂️👩‍💻

column1: 4. don’t let anxiety guide you. focus on the present
column2: believe that everything happens for a reason. even if a negative incident occurs if you think that something good will come out of it
column3: you instantly change the dynamics and you get control of the situation. be brave

column1: 192548;instagram;2019-01-26 17:33:51;FALSE;there’s a huge chapter of my life that could be ending soon and i want to share that with you all. december 2017 i was sexually assaulted and was a hot mess for much of 2018. the da had declined my right to justice because to some people a win loss ratio is more important that prosecuting a rapist. and then my case was forwarded to the military to handle. it’s almost coming to an end and i don’t know what their result will be but i am so glad i went through this process. it has been time consuming and very emotional but it has taught me a lot. this smile on my face is because i have gone through an extremely traumatic experience and has come out on top. i have learned how to be strong
column2: and how to better handle my emotions. don’t get me wrong
column3: this whole situation sucks but i can firmly say that i have done everything in my power to stand up to sexual violence and seek the justice i deserve. if i had to stand up in a court room tomorrow and tell my story of how it has happened to #metoo
column4: i would. there are people out there that can’t and i am thankful to be strong enough to do so. #endsexualviolence #endsexualassault #metoomovement;;en;#metoo

column1: 192639;instagram;2019-01-26 20:04:09;FALSE;"💜 i am astounded at the relentless support i have been receiving this last month in my community.
i’ve been trying to put together these words...
and there are none that encapsulate just how humbled i am at how diligent and supportive my tribe has been.

column2: broken and exhausted after one of the hardest months i have ever been through in some ways. 💜

column1: the fact that you all have taken the time to not only listen (which is sooo important)
column2: but to spring into action this past month has taught me exactly how powerful my community can be. and it is breathtaking. 💜

column1: i am beside myself at the strength and beauty that connection
i feel sooo much love right now.  i have never experienced any of this before.
this burden has been too immense to describe...
but i also carry with me the strength of every woman who has experienced this before and now completely internalize how much relentless grit is needed to continue forward. 💜

i won’t tag anyone in order to protect y’all like you have been protecting me this last month. you know who you are and through this experience i now know exactly who all of you are!!!! i am so moved. i feel so loved. i am humbled and deeply grateful. i don’t know what else to do except thank you.
perhaps the words will come to me later but at least for now...i know i am indebted to all of you. 💜

column1: 192645;instagram;2019-01-26 20:11:33;FALSE;"a couple of months ago i was drafting a post about the healing powers of research and reading after narcissistic abuse. about how vital it is to educate yourself on narcissism
column3: and emotional abuse in the aftermath of a relationship with an npd/aspd individual.

column2: i rambled on about how certain authors have become my heroes
column4: and how i literally carried psychopath free around with me like a security blanket at the bottom of my purse for the first few months of my healing journey. that book was greater than validation for me; it was my salvation. before i read it
column5: i had no desire to be alive. i did not understand what just happened to me or what i was dealing with. i just knew i felt awful and replaceable and unlovable and broken and unworthy all because a horrible person did a heartless thing. and then i read jackson’s book and i learned exactly what happened to me
column6: exactly what i was dealing with
column7: and that there are millions of other people who have experienced the same horrible people
column9: and they are all coping with the same level of pain and emotional trauma. #psychopathfree gave me the answers i needed at the time and most importantly
column10: it gave me hope. and hope was all i needed to stay alive.

column2: i received a dm from the publishers of psychopath free letting me know jackson’s new book was coming out soon and wanted to know if i’d be interested in an advanced copy. at first i thought it was a hoax; that my notes app was being hacked. but it wasn’t. it was just serendipitous timing.

column1: fast forward and whole again is here! in it jackson picks up where psychopath free leaves off. now that we know what we experienced
column2: here’s how we can heal from the trauma. i will be devouring all of its wisdom this weekend and i encourage you all to do the same. click on the recommended reading link in my bio to get your copy. 📚

column1: after reading marcus borg's intro to 1 thessalonians
column2: i am reading thessalonians! i'm at 1 thessalonians 3-4.

column1: it has been such a long time since i read through paul's letters. i am struck
column3: at how confusing it would be if this was the start of your #christian journey. imagine
column4: your first introduction to the church being based on this letter from a man who never met the earthly jesus. it's a lot.

column2: i am also struck by the call to purity. this is up and against dedicating your lives to god. there was a practice of sacred prostitution in the greek/roman way of religion. in the context of the word dedication
column3: i am imagining part of the command is to stop going to those temples. and part of it is to get control of yourself. and part of it is to not mistreat or take advantage of others sexually.

column1: i am also struck by the idea that getting control of themselves sexually is culturally contextual up against the gentile practice of sacred prostitution. when we consider sexual purity for today
column2: perhaps it is up and against practices of sexual mistreatment and/or taking advantage of others. #metoo

column3: what religious leaders are thinking when they endorse a certain politician that rhymes with rump when it is clear that he is in violation of this pauline exhortation. the text says
column4: ""whoever rejects these instructions … is rejecting god."" (v. 4:8). rump has rejected god. those religious leaders who endorse rump also reject god.

column1: the challenge for #leaders from paul is how to call people to better behavior without demoralizing them. gentle encouragement. he finishes with reminders of their loving deeds. how can we do that?

column2: i’ve come to the realization that i’ve stopped myself from doing things i’ve wanted to do or doing things that genuinely make me happy. i always find myself apologizing for being me
column3: because i was wrapped up in the idea of the opinion of others or what other people had to say. thats why my 1st goal for 2019 is to step out of my comfort zone and focus on me. you’d be surprised what can manifest when you do.

column1: although stepping out of your ""comfort zone” is easier said then done
column2: you have to be willing to take the step to push yourself. my 2nd goal of the year is to believe in myself more. i can be hard on myself and basically my worst critique
column3: being a bit of a perfectionist. i am learning that its okay to make mistakes or to fail
column4: as long as you do your best. find a way to pick yourself back up and try again.” — @tannyboo  #ourwomensvoices

column2: “your kids are in a toxic situation”—i don’t disagree!! but over my dead body will he have them alone half the time
column3: not until they can at least speak for themselves. he is the perfect daddy in the eyes of (almost) everyone outside of this house. although he’s been on better behavior the past few months
column4: i still wouldn’t trust him with the kids alone. he can try to display whatever image he’d like to outsiders—including judges—and he’ll likely trick them. he has! but i know the reality and i know the truth. as does everyone who’s experienced anything like this and knows when the right time to leave safely is. •

column3: i was determined to be there to march for myself and for all of the women out there who cannot raise their voices or walk that mile. it was one of the most rewarding and energizing experiences of my life. 💗♀️✊

column674: ухаживания приятны . но почему некоторые особи мужского пола ( иначе я их назвать не могу ) возомнили себе
column677: это легкодоступное средство удовлетворения своих физиологических потребностей ? почему им позволительно вести себя нахально
column679: распускать руки как только вздумается ? мне искренне страшно от того
column681: где любой мужчина может спокойно и в открытую посреди огромного города прижать беззащитную девушку и распускать свои грязные руки ! и
column684: ведь  эти девушки такие легкодоступные - иначе почему она в юбке  ? ! любое сопротивление воспринимается как  да она ломается просто  . это жестоко и несправедливо
column687: я никогда не могу чувствовать себя в полной безопасности
column688: особенно в окружении особей мужского пола . с дискриминацией
column691: взглядами и прикосновениями я сталкиваюсь часто в повседневной жизни . с грубым применением мужской силы я сталкиваюсь третий раз . и я больше всего в жизни не хочу снова почувствовать это ощущение беспомощности и унижения
column692: которое чувствует любая девушка - жертва домогательств . поэтому
column695: носить с собой газовый балончик и посетить хоть пару уроков самообороны

column1: be a man they will say.
let me tell you what this means.
be kind. be respectful. be open. learn to communicate. don’t be afraid to cry. don’t be afraid to be afraid. don’t lash out. don’t think being mean is cool. don’t think being cool is important.

be open. don’t feel like you have to hold everything in. don’t think you have to go through all your problems alone. don’t act like everything is ok if everything is not ok. don’t hurt yourself. don’t hurt others.
be strong. but not just physically strong
column2: be emotionally and spiritually strong. don’t worry about having a six pack and muscles that hold no purpose except to look a certain way. don’t focus solely on your exterior. don’t think you have to play sports that hurt your brain and your body to prove that you are strong. don’t get lost in sports. it’s ok to feel lost. ask for help.

column1: be fluid. don’t think you have to prescribe to labels. don’t be afraid to hug your friends. don’t be afraid to give your dad a kiss on the check. don’t think that being gay makes you less than. don’t think showing love to others makes you weak. show love always. wear whatever colors you want. grow your hair long. wear makeup. express yourself fully without limitations.
be polite. hold the door open for others. say please and thank you. remember to put the seat down. use your words to express how you feel
column2: not your fists. use your brain. admit when you are wrong. speak up when you see something you don’t agree with. stand up for others.

column1: be humble. don’t be proud. don’t let pride guide you. don’t let your ego get in the way of making smart choices. be honored by second place. be honored you got to play at all. understand your privilege. use it with grace and compassion.

follow the law. don’t touch anyone who hasn’t given you permission. don’t speed. buckle your seatbelt. respect women’s bodies. respect other men’s bodies. respect your body. don’t drink and drive. don’t drink too much. remember your choices will have consequences. think before you act. think before you do anything. be smart.
boys we can no longer just be boys. men it’s time we stood up and said no more to other men. #enough #timesup #metoo";;en;#enough

a rainha madeleine stowe fala sobre os projetos futuros como à nova série que irá estrear na netflix
column2: trabalho com o esposo brian benben e à viagem para dubai. °

column1: stowe também tocou em movimentos sociais recentes dentro de hollywood
column2: como a campanha #metoo para expor o assédio sexual na indústria. inicialmente ganhou força quando várias atrizes se manifestaram contra o magnata do cinema harvey weinstein.stowe
column3: um dos membros fundadores da apj
column4: relembrou a criação de uma escola no haiti após o devastador terremoto de 2010
column5: e continua a trabalhar para o acesso à educação para jovens do mundo todo. “eu vim de um contexto muito difícil
column6: pessoalmente. e senti que tinha grande sorte dentro disso. nós tínhamos um sistema social na américa na época que permitia que você ficasse à tona ... meu pai estava desesperadamente doente e minha mãe estava encarregada de cuidar dele e de três filhos porque ele não podia mais trabalhar. eu me sinto como se tivesse tido sorte na vida ”

column1: 192999;instagram;2019-01-27 06:47:40;TRUE;;"this post has been reported & removed 4 times. someone must feel pretty guilty. i dedicate this repost to the 6 women that have reached out to me that have also experienced a level of sexual misconduct & especially to the 2 that experienced it with people on my list. jamele h & michael n.
when i was a little girl i dreamed of falling in love 🥰

column2: i began to have cyber relations with a 25 year old man. he told me that i was his soulmate and he wanted to urinate on me to profess his love. i ended things because i knew something about it was wrong & he then threatened to kill himself. sergio p.
i had a flashback of an older cousin forcing me to perform oral sex at a very early age. i waited 9 years before asking my mom about it.
my first time performing oral sex was through force and intimidation by a college sophomore. javonte m.
i was cornered by 3 other students. they kept laughing about how far aj's fingers would go up my vagina. it was just us. that was one of the scariest moments of my life. luckily the bell rang. ...
a coach at my high school gave me a $100 with a note saying it was going to be our year. he invited me to the movies. jamele h.

my first vaginal sex experience was forced by a childhood friend a year older than me. he raped me. afterwards he said ""i couldn't let them *** at famu get to you first.... how does it feel to be a woman?"" later on i confronted him and he told me i was a liar and that i wanted it. at a much earlier point
column3: he told me that he lost his virginity to a woman at least in her 30's. michael n.

column2: i went to a classmates house to tutor him in physics. i got very drunk. he raped me. later on he acknowledged and apologized for his actions. very very healing & therapeutic. as.
